{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503275"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1978"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1978"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.14,0.05,0.02,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1978"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96504"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47940"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents with a two-month history of progressively increasing fatigue, nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain. Upon further inquiry, she reports hyperpigmentation of her skin, particularly on sun-exposed areas such as her neck and hands. She also complains of recurrent episodes of dizziness upon standing. She has a history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease for which she is taking esomeprazole. She denies any recent illnesses or changes in medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg lying down and drops to 80/50 mmHg upon standing. She appears dehydrated, with dry mucous membranes.\u003Cbr /\u003EHer laboratory findings are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb: 109 g/L (125 \u2013 160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWBCs: 6.9 x 10^9/L (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 235 x 10^9/L (150 \u2013 450 )\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum sodium: 125mmol/L (137 \u2013 145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 5.3mmol/L (3.5 \u2013 4.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting blood glucose: 2.5mmol/L (3.2 \u2013 5.5 )\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"The presence of antibodies against which enzyme would help to establish the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["21-hydroxylase","17-alpha-hydroxylase","11-beta-hydroxylase","Glutamic acid decarboxylase","Adrenocorticotropic hormone receptor"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of Addison\u0027s disease, including fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, hyperpigmentation, postural hypotension, and electrolyte abnormalities (hyponatraemia, hyperkalaemia, and hypoglycaemia), indicative of adrenal insufficiency. Autoantibodies against \u003Cstrong\u003E21-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E, an enzyme involved in the synthesis of cortisol and aldosterone, are commonly found in patients with autoimmune Addison\u0027s disease. These antibodies contribute to the destruction of adrenal cortical cells, leading to adrenal insufficiency and the characteristic symptoms observed in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003E17-alpha-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in glucocorticoid and androgen production, deficiencies in this enzyme typically present with symptoms of congenital adrenal hyperplasia. Females with complete 17\u03b1-hydroxylase deficiency are born with normal external female genitalia but may have underdeveloped internal reproductive organs. Those with partial deficiency may develop some secondary sexual characteristics. Chromosomally male individuals can present with abnormal external genitalia, which may appear female in appearance; a partial deficiency may have underdeveloped male genitalia. Both sexes are infertile. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E11-beta-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the production of both mineralocorticoids and cortisol, but it is not the target of autoantibodies in Addison\u0027s disease. Deficiencies in this enzyme can lead to hypertension, hypokalaemia, and metabolic alkalosis, which are not consistent with the presentation of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlutamic acid decarboxylase (GAD)\u003C/strong\u003E antibodies are associated with the development of type 1 diabetes mellitus, not Addison\u0027s disease. While autoimmune processes can affect multiple endocrine glands, GAD antibodies are not implicated in the pathogenesis of Addison\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibodies against \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are not associated with Addison\u0027s disease. ACTH receptors are targeted in other conditions, such as adrenal insufficiency due to impaired pituitary function, but not in autoimmune Addison\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Addison\u0027s disease is associated with the presence of antibodies against 21-hydroxylase.","Addison\u0027s disease presents with signs and symptoms including fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, hyperpigmentation, postural hypotension, and electrolyte abnormalities (hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypoglycemia)."],"references":["Salvi M et al, 1988. \u2018Role of Autoantibodies in the Pathogenesis and Association of Endocrine Autoimmune Disorders\u2019 in Endocrine Reviews, vol. 9, pp 450-466.","Munir S, Quintanilla Rodriguez BS, Waseem M. Addison Disease. [Updated 2024 Jan 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441994/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1978"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T09:38:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T09:44:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1978"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Grad